<TITLE> EU releases glowing survey ahead of reform summit </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRUSSELS, June 20 (bdnews24com/Reuters) - The European Commission hailed on Wednesday a survey published on the eve of a key EU summit that showed an increase in public support for the bloc, its institutions and the idea of an EU constitution. A spokesman for the EU executive noted that optimism was highest in Poland, despite its reputation as a "difficult partner" because of its opposition to parts of the blueprint for a new EU treaty championed by Germany. The Commission said all three main indicators of attitudes -- support for EU membership, perceived benefits of membership and the EU's image -- rose in the last six months by 4, 5 and 6 points to 57, 59 and 52 percent respectively. It said the level of trust for the Commission itself and the European Parliament showed a similar trend, each rising 4 points to 52 percent and 56 percent respectively over the same period. Two-thirds supported the idea of an EU constitution, a draft of which was rejected by French and Dutch voters in 2005, and just under half supported further enlargement of the bloc. Both scores represented gains of three percentage points. Commission spokesman Mikolaj Dowgielewicz said the survey showed "a significant majority" favouring EU-wide decision-making in fighting terrorism, protecting the environment and in defence and foreign affairs. "The general trend is very positive," he said. "This is of course a survey that comes at a very particular moment in time ... ahead of the crucial European Council," he said. The survey was carried out by pollster TNS for the Commission. Nearly 30,000 people were interviewed between April 10 and May 15 and the initial results are published on the EU website at www.ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/index_en.htm. Leaders of the 27 EU states meet on Thursday and Friday in Brussels to try to hammer out an agreement on reform of EU institutions needed to replace the failed constitutional treaty. Backers say the reform is needed to allow further enlargement of the blo